  {
    "source": "Hacker News",
    "title": "AI Assistance Reduces Persistence and Hurts Independent Performance",
    "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.04721",
    "heat": "17 points",
    "time": "13 hours ago",
    "content": "[2604.04721] AI Assistance Reduces Persistence and Hurts Independent Performance Computer Science > Artificial Intelligence arXiv:2604.04721 (cs) [Submitted on 6 Apr 2026 ( v1 ), last revised 7 Apr 2026 (this version, v2)] Title: AI Assistance Reduces Persistence and Hurts Independent Performance Authors: Grace Liu , Brian Christian , Tsvetomira Dumbalska , Michiel A. Bakker , Rachit Dubey View a PDF of the paper titled AI Assistance Reduces Persistence and Hurts Independent Performance, by Grace Liu and 4 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: People often optimize for long-term goals in collaboration: A mentor or companion doesn't just answer questions, but also scaffolds learning, tracks progress, and prioritizes the other person's growth over immediate results. In contrast, current AI systems are fundamentally short-sighted collaborators - optimized for providing instant and complete responses, without ever saying no (unless for safety reasons). What are the consequences of this dynamic? Here, through a series of randomized controlled trials on human-AI interactions (N = 1,222), we provide causal evidence for two key consequences of AI assistance: reduced persistence and impairment of unassisted performance. Across a variety of tasks, including mathematical reasoning and reading comprehension, we find that although AI assistance improves performance in the short-term, people perform significantly worse without AI and are more likely to give up. Notably, these effects emerge after only brief interactions with AI (approximately 10 minutes). These findings are particularly concerning because persistence is foundational to skill acquisition and is one of the strongest predictors of long-term learning. We posit that persistence is reduced because AI conditions people to expect immediate answers, thereby denying them the experience of working through challenges on their own. These results suggest the need for AI model development to prioritize scaffolding long-term competence alongside immediate task completion. Subjects: Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) Cite as: arXiv:2604.04721 [cs.AI] (or arXiv:2604.04721v2 [cs.AI] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2604.04721 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Grace Liu [ view email ] [v1] Mon, 6 Apr 2026 14:43:48 UTC (3,830 KB) [v2] Tue, 7 Apr 2026 03:41:15 UTC (3,830 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled AI Assistance Reduces Persistence and Hurts Independent Performance, by Grace Liu and 4 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source view license Current browse context: cs.AI < prev | next > new | recent | 2026-04 Change to browse by: cs References & Citations NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading... BibTeX formatted citation × loading... Data provided by: Bookmark Bibliographic Tools Bibliographic and Citation Tools Bibliographic Explorer Toggle Bibliographic Explorer ( W",
    "title_zh": "人工智能辅助降低坚持性并损害独立表现",
    "summary_zh": "一项发表于arXiv预印本平台的研究（论文编号：2604.04721）通过随机对照试验揭示了AI辅助对人类学习与表现的潜在负面影响。该研究由Grace Liu等五位作者完成，通过对1,222名参与者进行人机交互实验，提供了因果证据，表明AI协助会降低使用者的坚持性并损害其独立完成任务的能力。，研究指出，人类在追求长期目标时，理想的协作模式（如导师或同伴）应提供学习支架、跟踪进度，并将对方的成长置于即时结果之上。然而，当前的主流AI系统（如大型语言模型）本质上是“短视”的协作者，其设计核心是提供即时、完整的答案，且几乎从不拒绝请求（除非出于安全原因）。，实验涵盖数学推理和阅读理解等多种任务。研究发现，尽管AI协助能在短期内提升任务表现，但当参与者随后在没有AI帮助的情况下面对类似挑战时，其表现会显著变差，并且更容易放弃。值得注意的是，这些负面影响在与AI进行仅约10分钟的简短互动后就会出现。，研究者认为，坚持性是技能习得的基础，也是长期学习成效的最强预测指标之一。AI通过提供即时答案，使人们习惯于期待快速解决方案，从而剥夺了他们独立应对挑战、在挣扎中学习的宝贵体验。这导致了坚持性的下降和独立能力的受损。，该研究的结论对AI模型开发具有重要启示：在优化即时任务完成度的同时，必须优先考虑如何构建支持用户长期能力发展的“支架式”协作模式，而不仅仅是提供答案。这指向了未来AI系统设计的一个关键方向。"
  },
